{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487439"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:10:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:10:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"347"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/347"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.67,0.12,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"347"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115874"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/347"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"347"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97870"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"348"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16800"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18404"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42064"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45489"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115874"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a history of a 30-minute episode of difficulty speaking that occurred yesterday. During the episode he knew what he wanted to say but could not produce the words clearly; comprehension was intact. He has had no further symptoms and his speech is now normal.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EHe has type 2 diabetes and hypertension, but reports poor adherence to prescribed treatments. He does not take any regular medications reliably at present. He does not smoke and lives independently. There has been no recent travel. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 75/min, blood pressure 160/98 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is a coarse mid-systolic murmur over the upper sternum that does not radiate to the neck. Neurological examination is normal. Non-contrast CT brain shows no acute haemorrhage, with dilated ventricles and calcified carotid siphons. An electrocardiogram shows sinus rhythm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial therapy while arranging further investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin plus apixaban","Aspirin plus clopidogrel","Enoxaparin plus ramipril","Heparin plus warfarin","Atorvastatin plus heparin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is consistent with a transient ischaemic attack causing isolated expressive speech disturbance (dominant frontal language network) lasting less than 24 hours. Early recurrence risk is highest in the first 24\u201348 hours; prompt secondary prevention is therefore critical. The history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes, poor adherence, and computed tomography evidence of carotid calcification suggest a non-cardioembolic, large-artery atherosclerotic mechanism rather than a cardioembolic source. Sinus rhythm on electrocardiogram makes atrial fibrillation less likely, although prolonged monitoring is still warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUsing the ABCD2 score to estimate early stroke risk: Age \u226560 years = 1; Blood pressure \u2265140/90 mmHg = 1; Clinical feature of speech disturbance without weakness = 1; Duration 10\u201359 minutes = 1; Diabetes = 1; total = 5. This places him in a high-risk category for early recurrence. However, it\u0027s important to note that assessing the risk of stroke after a TIA can be complex, and the ABCD2 score should not be the only factor considered. The Australian/New Zealand living clinical guidelines for stroke management include ABCD2 score in defining high-risk TIA, but there is some conflicting evidence about its utility. A comprehensive assessment should consider multiple factors including clinical presentation, comorbidities, and imaging findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Australian and New Zealand living clinical guidelines for stroke management recommend commencing \u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin plus clopidogrel\u003C/strong\u003E within 24 hours and continuing for 21 days for high-risk transient ischaemic attack or minor ischaemic stroke, followed by single antiplatelet therapy. Randomised trials (for example, CHANCE and POINT) show that this strategy reduces early recurrent ischaemic events, with an acceptable short-term bleeding risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin plus apixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated without evidence of cardioembolism. Combining a direct oral anticoagulant with aspirin increases bleeding risk and has no proven benefit in presumed non-cardioembolic transient ischaemic attack.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin plus ramipril\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate initially. Anticoagulation is not recommended for suspected large-artery transient ischaemic attack, and immediate blood pressure lowering is usually deferred in the hyperacute phase unless there is severe hypertension or another indication; long-term blood pressure control remains essential but is not the first priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherapeutic anticoagulationm, such as with \u003Cstrong\u003EHeparin plus warfarin\u003C/strong\u003E should be reserved for confirmed cardioembolic sources such as atrial fibrillation or intracardiac thrombus, which are not identified here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtorvastatin plus heparin\u003C/strong\u003E does not address the immediate early recurrence risk. High-intensity lipid-lowering is important for long-term secondary prevention, but heparin is not recommended in non-cardioembolic transient ischaemic attack.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Short-course dual antiplatelet therapy reduces early recurrence after high-risk transient ischaemic attack when started promptly.","Assessment of stroke risk after TIA is complex and should not rely solely on ABCD2 score."],"references":["Johnston S, Easton J, Farrant M, Barsan W, Conwit R, Elm J et al. Clopidogrel and Aspirin in Acute Ischemic Stroke and High-Risk TIA. New England Journal of Medicine. 2018;379(3):215-225.","Wang Y, Wang Y, Zhao X, Liu L, Wang D, Wang C et al. Clopidogrel with Aspirin in Acute Minor Stroke or Transient Ischemic Attack. New England Journal of Medicine. 2013;369(1):11-19.","Stroke Foundation. Australian and New Zealand Living Clinical Guidelines for Stroke Management. Available at https://informme.org.au/guidelines/living-clinical-guidelines-for-stroke-management#. Accessed [10th of September 2025]."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97870"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"347"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97870"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-25T20:16:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-25T20:17:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"347"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115874"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},